# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: log-aggregation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] A **data logger** (also **datalogger** or **data recorder**) is an electronic device that records data over time or about location either with a built-in instrument or sensor or via external instruments and sensors.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Increasingly, but not entirely, they are based on a digital processor (or computer), and called digital data loggers (DDL).
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] They generally are small, battery-powered, portable, and equipped with a microprocessor, internal memory for data storage, and sensors.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Some data loggers interface with a personal computer and use software to activate the data logger and view and analyze the collected data, while others have a local interface device (keypad, LCD) and can be used as a stand-alone device.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Data loggers vary from general-purpose devices for various measurement applications to very specific devices for measuring in one environment or application type only.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] While it is common for general-purpose types to be programmable, many remain static machines with only a limited number or no changeable parameters.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Electronic data loggers have replaced chart recorders in many applications.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] One primary benefit of using data loggers is their ability to automatically collect data on a 24-hour basis.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Upon activation, data loggers are typically deployed and left unattended to measure and record information for the duration of the monitoring period.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] This allows for a comprehensive, accurate picture of the environmental conditions being monitored, such as air temperature and relative humidity.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] The cost of data loggers has been declining over the years as technology improves and costs are reduced.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Simple single-channel data loggers can cost as little as $25, while more complicated loggers may cost hundreds or thousands of dollars.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Standardization of protocols and data formats has been a problem but is now growing in the industry and XML, JSON, and YAML are increasingly being adopted for data exchange.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] The development of the Semantic Web and the Internet of Things is likely to accelerate this present trend.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Several protocols have been standardized including a smart protocol, SDI-12, that allows some instrumentation to be connected to a variety of data loggers.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] The use of this standard has not gained much acceptance outside the environmental industry.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] SDI-12 also supports multi-drop instruments.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Some data logging companies support the MODBUS standard.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] This has been used traditionally in the industrial control area, and many industrial instruments support this communication standard.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Another multi-drop protocol that is now starting to become more widely used is based upon CAN-Bus (ISO 11898).
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Some data loggers use a flexible scripting environment to adapt to various non-standard protocols.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] The terms data logging and data acquisition are often used interchangeably.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] However, in a historical context, they are quite different.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] A data logger is a data acquisition system, but a data acquisition system is not necessarily a data logger.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Data Loggers are changing more rapidly now than ever before.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] The original model of a stand-alone data logger is changed to one of a device that collects data but also has access to wireless communications for alarming of events, automatic reporting of data, and remote control.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Data loggers are beginning to serve web pages for current readings, e-mail their alarms, and FTP their daily results into databases or direct to the users.
[src:log-aggregation/data-logging] Very recently, there is a trend to move away from proprietary products with commercial software to open-source software and hardware devices.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:log-aggregation/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluentd was positioned for "big data," semi- or un-structured data sets.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] It analyzes event logs, application logs, and clickstreams.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] According to Suonsyrjä and Mikkonen, the "core idea of Fluentd is to be the unifying layer between different types of log inputs and outputs.", Fluentd is available on Linux, macOS, and Windows.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluentd was created by Sadayuki Furuhashi as a project of the Mountain View-based firm Treasure Data.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Written primarily in Ruby, its source code was released as open-source software in October 2011.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] The company announced $5 million of funding in 2013.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Treasure Data was then sold to Arm Ltd. in 2018.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluentd was one of the data collection tools recommended by Amazon Web Services in 2013, when it was said to be similar to Apache Flume or Scribe.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Google Cloud Platform's BigQuery recommends Fluentd as the default real-time data-ingestion tool, and uses Google's customized version of Fluentd, called google-fluent, as a default logging agent.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluent Bit is a log processor and log forwarder that is being developed as a CNCF sub-project under the umbrella of Fluent project.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluentd is written in C and Ruby and consumes at least 60 megabytes of memory.
[src:log-aggregation/fluentd] Fluent Bit is written only in C, with no dependencies, and consumes approximately one megabyte of memory, making it easier to run under embedded Linux and in containers.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] Logstash is an open source data collection engine with real-time pipelining capabilities.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] Logstash can dynamically unify data from disparate sources and normalize the data into destinations of your choice.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] Cleanse and democratize all your data for diverse advanced downstream analytics and visualization use cases.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] While Logstash originally drove innovation in log collection, its capabilities extend well beyond that use case.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] Any type of event can be enriched and transformed with a broad array of input, filter, and output plugins, with many native codecs further simplifying the ingestion process.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] Logstash accelerates your insights by harnessing a greater volume and variety of data.
[src:log-aggregation/introduction] You’ll use the Logstash Elasticsearch output plugin to send data to Elastic Cloud Serverless.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Build your OpenSearch solution using core tooling and visualizations.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Use vector database capabilities for more relevant search results.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Power your applications with machine learning model integration.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Explore and visualize your data using interactive dashboards.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Filter, mutate, and sample your data for ingestion into OpenSearch.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Interact with OpenSearch from your application using language APIs.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Measure OpenSearch cluster performance metrics.
[src:log-aggregation/latest] Simplify your upgrade or migration to OpenSearch.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:log-aggregation/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:log-aggregation/server-log] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:log-aggregation/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
